12684.title: evening dress
12684.creation_notes:
dress based on an earlier style from 1951?
for Traina-Norell
12684.description: black three piece ensemble; overdress trimmed with ostrich feathers; belted
12684.credit_line: Gift of Mrs. Mark Holeman in memory of Kathryne S. Block
12684.provenance: Kathryne S. Block; Mrs. Mark Holeman, Indianapolis; given to the Indianapolis Museum of Art (1985).

extended_text.content:
Throughout his career, Norman Norell produced ready-to- wear garments that were of the same caliber as any made-to-order garments fashioned by European couturiers. His creations were sold across the country in upscale department and specialty stores.

One of the most popular Norell silhouettes had a fitted waist and a full skirt, as seen here. The bodice of this dress consists of narrow stitched tucks throughout, and the skirt has loose hand-knifed narrow pleats. The skirt’s bottom is edged with dyed ostrich feathers, which had become popular as a substitute for fur and appeared in both day and evening wear in Norell’s Fall 1951 collection.
extended_text.title: Gallery Label

36275.title: wedding dress
36275.description: rich brown two-piece wedding dress asymmetrical pleating and draping
36275.credit_line: Gift of Mr. Robert C. Martindale
36275.provenance:
Mr. Robert C. Martinsdale (1), Indianapolis; given to Indianapolis Museum of Art (1974).
(1) Worn by Alice Morrison at her wedding to Robert Wier Cathcart in Indianapolis on May 11, 1871.

extended_text.content:
Alice Morrison wore this dress on May 11, 1871, when she was married at her parents' home, located at the southwest corner of Tennessee and Vermont Streets in Indianapolis.

The style of the skirt is typical of the late 1860s and early 1870s, when the fullness was gathered up in the back and a bustle was worn to support accentuated draping on the hips.

In the 1800s, it was common for brides to wear colorful dresses on their wedding day. The tradition often called for the bride to wear the wedding dress to various balls and receptions during the first year of her marriage.
extended_text.title: Gallery Label

Oldenburg often worked in traditional print media transferring the preparatory drawings for his monumental sculptures into color lithographs.

27342.title: Wall Chart I
27342.credit_line: Emma Harter Sweetser, James V. Sweetser, Mary and Agness Wetsell Fund
27342.inscription: signed and dated in pencil, L.L.:  L.P. imp Jim Dine 1974
rights: © Jim Dine/Artists Rights Society (ARS), New York

extended_text.content:
Using four lithographic stones, three plates and 49 colors, Dine comments humorously on the interrelationships of colors and words on flat surfaces.

Inspired by bathroom tiles that Dine had made in his kiln in Putney, Vermont, Wall Chart I resurrects his use of common household objects to expound on art theory that had begun in 1963 with his painting Red Devil Color Chart No. 2.
extended_text.title: Gallery Label

Landfall Press was the first major print workshop to encourage the graphic expression of Conceptual Art.

extended_text.content:
Rauschenberg introduced his unusual "combines" in 1954, marrying gestures of paint with three-dimensional found objects and collaged photographic images.

Rauschenberg's paintings and prints, improvised from objects he would find on any given day, laid the groundwork for Pop art's fascination with commonplace, everyday objects.
